 clear the much higher hurdle of designing credible guarantees on the terms of agreement--something that is difficult without outside assistance. Examining conflicts from Greece to Laos, China to Columbia, Bosnia to Rwanda, Walter confirms just how crucial the prospect of third-party security guarantees and effective power-sharing pacts can be--and that adversaries do, in fact, consider such factors in deciding whether to negotiate or fight. While taking many other variables into account and acknowledging that third parties must also weigh the costs and benefits of involvement in civil war resolution, this study reveals not only how peace is possible, but probable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCivil war. 0aLow-intensity conflicts (Military science). 0aWorld politicsy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aAddis Ababa agreement (1993).  aAfghanistan.  aAmerican Civil War.  aAngola.  aArusha accords.  aBaumhoegger, Goswin.  aBoutros-Ghali, Boutros.  aCallaghan, James.  aEl Salvador.  aGeneva peace agreement.  aHabyarimana, Juvénal.  aJohnson, Phyllis.  aKarker, Hassame.  aKing, Charles.  aLancaster House negotiations.  aLaos.  aLebanon.  aNicaragua.  aRhodesian Front.  aTela agreement.  aTouval, Saadia.  aUnited Nations.  aUniversity of Michigan.  aVictoria Falls Conference.  aYoung, Andrew.  aZambia.  aautonomous regions.  abalance of power.  acease-fire agreements.  acosts of war.  acredible commitment theory.  ademocracy-autocracy scale.  adivisibility of stakes.  aethics of intervention.  afederalism.  ahegemony.  ahypotheses.  alogit analysis.  amediation.  amilitary consolidation.  amonitoring and verification.  amultivariate regression analysis.  aone-party rule.  aparliamentar